emphatically annunciatory texts, she demonstrates how the extreme possibilities of expression that they present through specific citational and rhetorical praxes render the language of announcement overdetermined and anachronistic in ways that exceed any systematic account of historical time and experience. This excess in and through language is precisely what opens hitherto unheard of alternatives for conceiving of historical temporality and political possibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aNew and old. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847756540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438477565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438477565/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles